eventData.headline: Students for Carbon Dividends
eventData.description:
Students for Carbon Dividends is a nationwide group of student leaders harnessing energy and passion to light a path towards a bipartisan climate breakthrough. The carbon dividends strategy is already supported by the broadest climate coalition in American history, including the largest statement of economists of all time. It is also endorsed by hundreds of Student Body Presidents from all 50 states—the largest declaration of student leaders in US history.

That's because carbon dividends is a solution where all sides would win. It would cut emissions fast, while also driving clean energy innovation, creating jobs, protecting our families and communities, and ensuring continued opportunity and prosperity.
Together, we can save the world (actually). We invite you to join us in making history.

Join us to learn how we engage in Congressional action, navigate the climate sphere and unite hundreds of students across the country towards the biggest bipartisan climate breakthrough in history.

eventData.headline: Yale Undergraduate Research Journal (YURJ)
eventData.description:
The Yale Undergraduate Research Journal was established in the spring of 2020 and is the first reviewed publication to span the disciplinary breadth of research conducted by Yale students.  Twice a year, YURJ publishes recent work from the Humanities, Social Sciences, and STEM fields online and in print. Symposia, YURJ’s sister publication, conducts various interviews and profiles in collaboration with the Yale Undergraduate Research Association.

The Yale Undergraduate Research Journal, in collaboration with other large campus publications like the Yale Daily News, Yale Scientific Magazine, and Accent - is hosting a panel of representatives from Yale undergraduate publications spanning a wide array of subjects and formats.

At this panel, prospective Yalies will be able to hear about the plethora of publishing opportunities at Yale - from creative writing to scientific research manuscripts - and the many ways that Yalies get involved with the production of these issues. From authorship to production to business management, there are tons of ways to become part of the exciting world of Yale student publications - at this panel, you'll be able to hear about them all! Panelists include: Yale Daily News, Yale Literary Magazine, Yale Scientific, The Yale Globalist, and Accent Multilingual Magazine.

eventData.headline: Glee Club
eventData.description: Meet and talk with members of the Yale Glee Club! We are Yale’s principal undergraduate mixed choir and oldest musical organization, currently in our 160th season. We sing many different kinds of music, including contemporary choral music, spirituals & folk songs, world music, big choral pieces with orchestra, and of course, traditional Yale songs. In this session, we will be listening to some past recordings and answering any questions you may have about the audition process, what it's like to be in YGC, our favorite Glee memories, and more! https://gleeclub.yalecollege.yale.edu/

eventData.headline: Christian Union Lux
eventData.description:
Christian Union Lux is a Christian fellowship and undergraduate organization at Yale University. CU Lux’s shared mission is to transform our nation and world by developing and connecting bold Christian leaders. We provide an in-depth study of Scripture, Christian leadership training, mentoring, fellowship, and support for Christian students. We also provide resources and opportunities to help any interested students — whatever their spiritual background or beliefs — learn more about Christianity. Our main activities include Bible courses, a bi-weekly lecture series called “Rooted,” retreats, and various on-campus outreaches.

COME JOIN THE CHRISTIAN UNION CAROUSEL, APRIL 30TH, 6:30-9:00PM EST! Drop into this Zoom and loop through different breakout rooms to learn about who we are as an organization, meet our student team, and socialize with the CU community!

eventData.headline: Yale Out of the Blue
eventData.description:
Out of the Blue is Yale University's award-winning contemporary A Cappella group, known for its tight vocals and electric performance style. Founded in 1986 by a group of eight students determined to create a new brand of "Yale A Cappella," Out of the Blue (OOTB, pronounced OOT-bah) has evolved into Yale's most dynamic vocal group, entertaining audiences near and far with an eclectic repertoire of current and classic pop, rock, R&B, jazz, and dubstep.

Come and hang out with Yale Out Of The Blue and get to know us! Information on Yale a cappella, rush and recruitment, as well as zoom fun and games!

eventData.headline: First-Gen, Low-Income Advocacy Movement
eventData.description:
Student Org Event: Yale First-Generation and/or Low-Income Advocacy Movement

We are a coalition dedicated to advocacy and community-building for all First-generation and/or low-income students at Yale!

Throughout the year, we form task forces based on the projects that members want to work on, such as FGLI student-faculty mixers, financial aid literacy, and advocating for a FGLI-dedicated space on campus. In the midst of all of this advocacy, we also make sure to foster a safe space for FGLI folks to bond and form deeper relationships - if we don't support each other, who will?

Come meet the FAM! Join YFAM to meet fellow First-Generation and/or Low-Income students for an informal discussion about what it means to be FGLI at Yale.
Discussion will cover important resources, tips, and strategies for success.
